            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Adam Kaplan\u2019s life is a story of deliberate ascent. Raised in a comfortable, if unremarkable, Long Island suburb by a dentist father and a high school history teacher mother, Adam was instilled with a belief in clear, attainable goals. He was smart, diligent, but never the flashiest person in the room. He pursued a computer science degree in the mid-90s, more for its practical applications than any burning passion for code.\n\nThe siren song of the first dot-com boom lured him to San Francisco in 1999. He arrived with a solid engineering job and a sense of infinite possibility, only to watch it all crumble a year later. Surviving the bust was his defining professional turning point. While friends chased fleeting startup glory, Adam saw the value of stable architecture. He returned to school for his MBA, determined to pivot from building the product to directing its path. This calculated move paid off, leading to a steady, impressive climb up the product management ladder at a series of established tech firms.\n\nHis personal life followed a similarly planned trajectory, until it didn't. He married in his early thirties, had a daughter, Chloe, and bought a handsome Edwardian in Noe Valley. But the quiet pressures of two demanding careers created a slow, seismic drift, culminating in an amicable but painful divorce five years ago. Now, his life is meticulously structured. Weekdays begin with the 7:45 AM company shuttle to his SoMa office, a day of back-to-back meetings, and an evening run through his neighborhood's hilly streets. Weekends are for Chloe\u2014soccer games at a park in the Mission, trips to the Ferry Building Farmer's Market, and navigating the complexities of co-parenting.\n\nAt 48, Adam has achieved the financial security his parents prized. He appreciates San Francisco for its beauty and dynamism, yet feels insulated from its raw energy. He finds himself staring out his bay window, wondering what the next chapter holds. The corporate grind feels less like an achievement and more like a gilded cage. He dreams not of a bigger title, but of something smaller, more tangible\u2014perhaps consulting for a non-profit, or simply having the time to find a relationship built on something other than mutual ambition. He has the metrics of a successful life but is quietly searching for its meaning."
