            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the silence of the SoMa warehouse office in 2001. A week before, it was a hive of frantic energy. Now, it was just rows of empty Aeron chairs and a Ping-Pong table gathering dust. The primary color logo on the wall felt like a cruel joke. It wasn't failure that hit him, but a cold, clarifying fear. In that quiet, cavernous space, Adam decided he would never again build his life on something so flimsy. The experience didn\u2019t just make him cautious; it made him calculated, building a career like a fortress.\n\n***\n\n2.\nAfter closing on the Noe Valley Edwardian, he and his then-wife sat on the floor of the empty living room, sharing a bottle of champagne from paper cups. The late afternoon sun streamed through the bay window, illuminating dust motes dancing in the air. He felt a profound, almost terrifying sense of rightness, as if he\u2019d just locked in the final, most important metric of a successful life. He didn\u2019t know then that the house would outlast the marriage, or that the beautiful window would one day feel like a frame for everything he was missing.\n\n***\n\n3.\nThe divorce wasn\u2019t one moment, but he remembers the one that made it real. They sat at the kitchen table, their expensive wedding china unused in the cabinet behind them. No shouting, just an exhausted quiet. He looked at her and saw not his partner, but a capable colleague with whom he'd run a difficult, multi-year project called 'family'. The project was ending. The grief was immense, but it was the quiet grief of a spreadsheet that just won't balance, a plan precisely executed that still yielded the wrong result.\n\n***\n\n4.\nChloe was eight, and she\u2019d fallen asleep against his chest while he was reading to her. He could feel her small, even breaths and the specific weight of her head on his shoulder. In that moment, the entire scaffolding of his life\u2014the promotions, the stock options, the strategic plans\u2014felt like a flimsy and irrelevant abstraction. This was real. Her hand clutching his shirt was the only KPI that mattered. That feeling has since become his compass, pointing him toward a truth his ambition had long obscured.\n\n***\n\n5.\nOn a recent run, he reached the crest of 24th Street, gasping in the cool evening air. Below, the city sprawled out in a grid of glittering lights, a perfect, logical system he helped maintain. He could see his office tower, a distant, silent monolith. He felt a sudden, dizzying detachment, like an astronaut looking at a planet he was no longer a part of. The financial security was there, the view was spectacular, but the connection was gone. He realized he wasn\u2019t running toward anything anymore; he was just running."
